It means I sit through movies that I might not like but that’s better than going in with false expectations and the feeling of liking something you never thought you would going in can’t be rivalled when it comes to media. text: Honestly, after Rogue One's success at capturing a pretty decent Star Wars movie, I was optimistic that The Last Jedi would be decent as well... maybe the writers and directors learned from the force awakens. I was wrong. It's like they just take concepts from every star wars movie, put it in a blender and serve it up and call it a star wars movie. There's no destination that it's going to. Before Disney's acquisition of Star Wars, the single moment that the movies built up to was the redemption of Anakin Skywalker. That was it. Now, it's all just one big star wars smoothie and I don't have any desire to continue watching the franchise. I'm done. It's heartbreaking to even say that, but Disney ripped my childhood out with the force awakens and stomped on it with the last Jedi.  I'm done with Star Wars and Kathleen Kennedy.

text: For me, it's the music that feels lack-luster...I know that John Williams doesn't have the time to score ALL the SW films, and I don't blame him for putting all his effort in the "Bigger" one's (Last Jedi was one of his best scores yet!), but John Powell's take on the music/score just feels weird.  Michael Giacchino even did a decent job of taking William's formula, and putting his own spin on it for Rogue one. It wasn't great, but it also didn't distract and make it obvious...but this just feels too much on the side of Blade Runner, Tron, or Trent Reznor's soundtrack for The Social Network, which are all fantastic soundtracks, but that's because it fits the film properly.  Half of what makes Star Wars feel like Star Wars is the powerful storytelling through the music, and if you're tasked with handling the music that is so iconic to the franchise, I wouldn't divert from what it's known for and turn it into another synthetic sounding sci-fi.

text: Dear Star Wars Fanbase (SPOILERS FOR THE NEW FILMS),  In 1977, the world was blown away by a new movie called "Star Wars." When the sequel came out a few years later, people hated it because it went a new route the people at first didn't like. However, the movie later on to become seen as a great film and eventually the best of the entire series. Return of the Jedi releases a few years later, it also was received well, although you guys were divided over Ewoks.   Cut to 1999, The Phantom Menace is released, after such loads of hype, you guys hated the film and the later two because of the quality. Honestly, I don't blame you. When I was a kid, they were my favorite of the series, but as an adult, I know they aren't good movies. Here's the thing: they could've been much worse. The prequels did have some upsides, such as the combat, some of the casting, and the potential story.  Cut to 2015, The Force Awakens is released (the first film without Lucas involved), you guys are divided over the film because of various reasons. The biggest one is the film was an exact copy of Episode IV. No it was not. It had similar story elements, but it was not an exact copy. The film wouldn't have furthered the franchise if it were the case. Cut to 2017, The Last Jedi is released. You guys are even more divided because of the risks it took as a Star Wars movie. In fact, you are so divided you attack other people who disagree with you.   One question: Why? Just why? Why do you have to behave so rabidly over a Sci-Fi Fantasy series? Criticizing filmmaking decisions is one thing, but ranting over things that didn't please you, like the lack of deep lore, or fan theories not coming true, or just not getting what you guys exactly wanted is not fair. I LOVED The Last Jedi, I didn't think it was perfect (no movie is, not even the original trilogy), but I still was captivated and moved by the film. Star Wars is a super fun movie franchise, and hating on the new movies just because Snoke died or a not-that-badly executed Casino scene is just plain dumb. Give the new movies a chance. The series is NOT ruined not one bit. You guys have said that when Empire came out, when the prequels came out, and when the new films came out, when that was never EVER the case. It's just taking new directions and that's okay. If it didn't Star Wars would have actually died. So please, all I'm asking of you is just give a fair opinion on the films based on what they are, and not your own desires. Disney has not ruined Star Wars and I don't believe they will, because unlike the prequels, their films take Star Wars to a new direction the RIGHT way. Be more open and be more fair. Please.  Love, A Star Wars fan

Critics aren't bad people for having an opinion and those who like Disney's direction aren't either. text: I think I'm pretty well done with Star Wars.  Disney just wants it to be the next Marvel and they're not doing anything interesting with the franchise. Playing it safe within the confines of the OT timeframe for it's "Story" movies and making their new Trilogy up as they go along while copying as much as possible from the OT.  I don't know how anyone can see it as different or fresh. Everything they've done is boring, predictable and safe.  I really did have high hopes that Disney would do something new and interesting with the franchise, but it's obviously just a cashcow to them, being fueled with nostalgia to keep people hooked. Oh, I'm sure there will be as much fan service show horned into this movie as possible. Jabba, Boba Fett, Greedo, some background droids, the kessel run, blah, blah, blah. Episode 8 was the first Star Was movies I wanted to leave partway through (didn't because I was with other people) and now Solo is the first one I have no desire to see at all.

To me, this looks like a really exciting heist-themed Star Wars movie about someone who is attempting things with his face and voice to try to look and sound like Harrison Ford.  Not saying he's not a good actor, or that it won't be a good film.  There's just no replacing Harrison Ford, in my book, and that's going to be a barrier for me going in to this film.  That being said, I hope it's great, and I hope it does the character (and legendary performance) justice.

text: What is going on with the tone of this trailer?  The original trilogy has a very specific sound design and visual aesthetic where you can look at any shot without much context and know that 'this is star wars'. This is getting very far away from a sound design or even an aesthetic that evokes Star Wars anymore... This is too generic. Generic electronic trailer music, generic trailer funny moment where the music stops, generic teamup line, generic shot at a romantic hook......  I get that the movies are moving into a new era and appealing to a new demographic but I don't see why it has to get so far away from the originals to accomplish this.

text: I'm hoping that some serious and goodhearted debate can start from this, even if I start on a slightly harsh tone... I'm really curious here.  Why is it that people mind seeing people of color on screen? Is it because you're disgusted by people who are not white? Is it because you're too used to seeing white people in most of your movies that when some movies deviate from that formula, your entire world view collapses?   You do understand that the heroes Hollywood put up on the screen have a massive effect on the self-perception of a lot of people of color, right?   I've watched movies since 1990 (that I am aware of) and I would be hardpressed to find ANY brown coloured hero in a Hollywood movie. My heroes were always white, a few black and even few Asian. So for a guy like me who has and STILL HAS hundreds of white colored heroes, mostly men, it's REFRESHING that Hollywood is now opening up the goodiebag and offering more heroes and more belief in the inner qualities of people despite their skin colour or gender.   I extremely rarely find people who are not white that have this problem and I hate to be the one to generalise... but it seems to be a white male problem. Black, brown, yellow... we've all had and still have tons of heroes that look like you. Why does it hurt you so much to have heroes that look like me?  Look forward to nuanced and thoughtful comments below. :-)

My hope is that the standalone movies can continue in the tradition of R1 and offer SW that appeals to all types of fans. The more divisive takes on SW - "burn down the past" etc - can be reserved for the trilogy films, but keep the standalones designed to be less controversial across the fandom. The trilogy films may also be the better place to skew a bit younger, with stuff like porgs or Marvel humor, with the idea being to bring younger audiences into the fold.  Anyhow looking forward to seeing this.

text: So... I think I like it. However, I am struggling with seeing these characters from the Original trilogy, outside of its specific whimsical atmosphere, without pondering good and evil, without family conflict rooted in that morality. It's as though they inhabit a different franchise now.   A great deal of this may be the aesthetic changes also, there is a lot of CGI and crisp interiors in this trailer. However I think my own issue is the former. Star Wars was mythology; a father and son conflict over morality, using fantasy archetypes, with a space opera levity and aesthetic.  It hasn't been that since the originals which is fine, it's a hard thing to franchise out (regarding narrative not merchandise) which is why everything that isn't the originals is different (the exception being the Force Awakens which is similar). The Prequels are an attempt at tragedy, Rogue One is an average war film, and The Last Jedi changed the rules specifically to get away from the constrictive mythology formula of the Originals - one of the major complaints from people was that Luke wasn't the same character, the tone and his actions were wrong.  What do you think?

text: Little throwaway lines in the original movie that mention things like the Clone Wars and the Kessel Run suggested a larger world with a history surrounding the details of events we were watching.  It had the effect of EXPANDING the world by hinting there's more going on than we'll ever witness.By making movies to dramatize every detail of every element ever mentioned, the effect is to SHRINK the fictional world by suggesting that ONLY those events and these characters are of any significance. Star Wars SHOULD be expanding into new stories about new people doing new things - exploring the potential set up in that first movie.  By staying in the bounds of what's known to the audience already the potential is denied and frankly I'm not sure how we're supposed to continue to care.  This trailer offers nothing but nostalgia as incentive to see the film.  You'll get to see the things you know about!  Gosh.  If there were no existing Star Wars films, no one would find this trailer interesting.

text: It's not supposed to feel like a SW movie! Neither did Rogue One. These are separate stories outside of the trilogy formula, get it? Different actors, different music (Thank Eris!), more action, different overall feel, etc. I for one am relieved that something OTHER than the typical, BORING, all-too-familiar music is being replaced, as in Rogue One. My only gripe is how they incorporate the Millennium Falcon this early in Han's piloting career. He's supposed to be a gambler, a hustler, a rogue, renegade, roustabout, and a scoundrel, so why couldn't they have introduced a whole plethora of borrowed, hijacked, and stolen spaceships, all with different designs, layouts, sizes, shapes, and functions to add more interest factor to Han's colorful and dangerous life story? Regardless, I AM excited to see more of this Outside-The-Trilogy storytelling. It's definitely a refreshing change...

text: Take Chewbacca, the Falcon, and the Imperial Star Destroyer out of this trailer. Without any of those things, you can’t tell me that you would have any idea that this wasn’t some Star Trek, Marvel, or any other movie that’s not Star Wars. And THAT’s the problem that I have with this trailer.   I’m not going to be another whiney fanboy. I hope it does well. But admittedly, this trailer didn’t quite give me any feeling of Star Wars. It’s just some sci-fi flick. And no, it’s not because I overhyped this trailer to the point of being disappointed with anything less than my expectations. I had no expectations going in and now, post trailer, I’m rather doubtful.

text: One of the true realities of these past couple of years is that we, the fans, are distorting our own view of Star Wars, where we forget that even the original trilogy was full of flaws. We have a fake ideal of what the correct Star Wars feel is, that no matter what we see, as long as it's not that ideal picture in each individuals mind, it will be wrong. The Expanded Universe both gave us more Star Wars to hold on to, but it also gave each individual their own view of what's Star Wars and what isn't. So what is really ruining this movie? We are, and that's why, simply go to this movie with a fresh mind giving it a chance. Why complain now? Enjoy and be critics afterwards. Share your opinions, but don't convert opinions to generalized facts.

text: Movie doesn't look bad, but Ehrenreich seems like a big time casting failure.   It's surprising to me, because I always figured leading parts in big tentpole movies are casted carefully and after numerous screen tests (Christian Bale in Batman Begins and Tom Hardy in TDKR spring to mind). I can't believe him not having what it takes to do the part wasn't apparent during pre-production.   Disney could've even approached the situation like Zemeckis did with Back to the Future, i. e. fire the bad actor and re-shoot the film from the start. In today's day and age though, that would probably be a PR and marketing nightmare, so they just gutted it out.   It's a shame, because the film looks solid otherwise.

text: This might end up being a surprisingly good/funny movie, but I doubt it, judging from the trailer alone.  The story is too cliche to be genuinely interesting.  It follows the same pattern as the rebooted "Star Trek's" Captain Kirk when he was a kid.  "I did something illegal, tried to outrun the police but got caught. I eventually got noticed by a guy who admired my illegal antics.  He took me in and raised me.  He taught me everything I know."  Neo from the Matrix comes to mind.    My theory for the reason that this is so cringeworthy is that it's just so cliche.  Why make this movie about something we never wanted to see?  You need mystery of a character to keep them 'mysterious'.  Telling every single facet of their early life and how they came to be the mysterious character you loved, is not necessary, nor is it asked for.  This movie (again, just judging from the trailer alone) doesn't seem to offer any new ideas or at least old ideas done with a sense of creativity.  I am just so tired of the saturation of the franchise concept.  Make something original with a massive budget like this one.  All you're really doing, with these kinds of movies, is making a billion dollar "done it before" movie that'll be in the bargain bin right next to Aladdin 2: Return of Jafar.

text: I loving seeing the comments complaining that there is "SJW" casting in this. You have literally 3 white people, 2 black people(One of which is Lando, unless you think he should be white), 2  aliens, and a robot. It's like they put a black person or a woman in the trailers and the internet lurkers start screaming "SJW!"  My major grip about this movie is that I didn't hear anyone asking for it. It isn't a story we needed to see. I have heard tons of people wanting a Obi Wan movie, but nothing about Solo, yet, hear we are. If they wanted to pull something out of this era, do a freaking Lando movie. I would have loved to see his rise to power. Something different and new. I actually enjoyed Force Awakens and Rogue One and thought Disney was off to a good start. With how bad TLJ was idk anymore. I have my doubts about this movie. I really don't care too much about it. I like Glover for Lando, but that is about it. I think Clarke is ok in GoT but she has been absolutely wooden in everything else.
